re societies. Examining black mothers’ engagements with attachment parenting, Hamilton shows the limitations of this neoliberal approach. Unique in its intersectional analysis of contemporary mothering ideologies, this outstanding book fills a gap in the literature on parenting culture studies, drawing on black feminist theorizing to analyse intensive mothering practices and policies. Black Mothers and Attachment Parenting is shortlisted for the 2021 BSA Philip Abrams Memorial Prize.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAttachment behavior in infants. 0aMotherhoodzCanada. 0aMotherhoodzGreat Britain. 0aParentingxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aParentingxSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 0aWomen, Black. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311119671840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781529207965423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781529207965/original  a978-3-11-119671-8  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles